+++ b/docs/adr/0001-monetary-amount-input-validation.md
+# ADR 0001 — Input-boundary validation for monetary amounts
+
+- **Status:** Accepted
+- **Date:** 2026-05-27
+- **Deciders:** Solution Architect
+- **Area:** `src/features/ledger` (amounts), ingestion adapters (SMS/OCR, Plaid)
+
+## Context
+
+Monetary amounts are the core data type of the ledger, but the codebase has no
+validation boundary for them:
+
+- `Transaction.amount` is a plain `number` (`src/features/ledger/types.ts:8`).
+  The sign carries meaning — **positive = income (credit), negative = expense
+  (debit)** — and downstream code depends on that convention
+  (`wealth-score/lib/compute.ts:14-24`, `:77-89` split income/expense on sign;
+  `lib/format.ts:20` formats signed currency).
+- Amounts are USD with two decimal places throughout
+  (`features/ledger/data.ts`, `lib/format.ts:1-6`).
+- There is **no parsing or validation layer** anywhere. `grep` for
+  `parseFloat`/`Number(`/`validate` across `src/` finds only consumers, no
+  guards. Amounts enter today exclusively through typed mock data
+  (`data.ts`); the live ingestion adapters named in the README (Twilio SMS/MMS
+  → Gemini OCR, Plaid bank feed) are **not yet built** — so there is no point
+  where an untrusted amount is currently checked before becoming a
+  `Transaction`.
+
+Consequently a malformed amount — negative where a magnitude is expected,
+non-numeric OCR output, sub-cent precision, or an out-of-range parse error
+(`$58,000` read as `5800000`) — would flow straight into balances, tax
+reserves, and the wealth-score valuation, corrupting the books with no signal.
+
+## Decision
+
+Introduce a **pure-function validation boundary** that every amount passes
+through before becoming a `Transaction.amount`, keeping the canonical
+representation a signed 2-decimal `number` (no representation change).
+
+- `src/features/ledger/lib/amount.ts` — `parseAmount(raw, direction)` returns a
+  discriminated `{ ok: true, value } | { ok: false, error }`. It coerces
+  number/string input (tolerating `$`, `,`, whitespace), then rejects: empty,
+  non-numeric, non-finite, negative magnitude, zero, > 2 decimal places, and
+  magnitude > `MAX_AMOUNT` ($1,000,000). Direction (`credit`/`debit`) sets the
+  stored sign. `isValidSignedAmount(amount)` re-asserts the same invariants on
+  an already-signed stored value. `explainAmountError` yields a user-facing
+  message for the SMS reply / review queue.
+- `src/features/ledger/lib/ingest.ts` — `ingestTransaction` /
+  `ingestTransactions` map a `RawTransaction` (amount as `unknown` magnitude +
+  `direction`) into a canonical `Transaction`, partitioning input into
+  `accepted` and `rejected`. This is the single seam the future SMS/OCR and
+  Plaid adapters call.
+
+This follows the repo's existing convention: co-located, pure, side-effect-free
+validation libs (`customers/lib/normalize.ts`, `benchmarks/lib/categorize.ts`),
+exported through the feature barrel (`features/ledger/index.ts`).
+
+**Alternative considered — integer-cents representation.** Storing amounts as
+integer cents eliminates floating-point drift entirely. Rejected *for now*: it
+is a breaking change touching every amount consumer (`format.ts`,
+`wealth-score`, `benchmarks`, all `data.ts` fixtures) for a scaffold whose data
+is still mocked. We mitigate FP drift instead by canonicalizing to 2 decimals
+(round with ε) and rejecting sub-cent precision at the boundary. The cents
+migration is recorded as a **follow-up ADR trigger** for when persistence
+(Cloud SQL) is introduced.
+
+## Consequences
+
+- **Positive:** one auditable boundary; malformed amounts are rejected with a
+  typed reason instead of silently corrupting balances; no representation
+  churn, so no consumer changes required; rejections carry a human message
+  ready for the SMS/review surfaces.
+- **Negative / residual risk:** amounts remain IEEE-754 floats — large sums
+  across many rows can still accumulate sub-cent drift in aggregates
+  (`computeSDE`). Bounded by the per-transaction ceiling and 2-decimal
+  canonicalization; the integer-cents migration remains the durable fix.
+- **Carried forward:** sign convention (credit +, debit −) is now codified at
+  the boundary, not just by convention — future adapters must supply
+  `direction` rather than a pre-signed amount.
+- **Testing:** the unit-test runner is now wired (`tsx` + Node's built-in test
+  runner). `npm test` globs `src/**/*.test.ts`; the validator suite runs green
+  (12/12). See the addendum.
+
+## Coverage / verification
+
+- Inspected: `ledger/types.ts`, `ledger/data.ts`, `lib/format.ts`,
+  `wealth-score/lib/compute.ts`, `customers/lib/normalize.ts`,
+  `features/ledger/index.ts`. Sign + precision convention confirmed empirically.
+- `tsc --noEmit` clean for the new modules (one pre-existing unrelated error in
+  `e2e/benchmarks-compare.unit.spec.ts`).
+- Validator logic verified: 12/12 boundary cases + signed-guard checks pass.
+
+## Addendum — 2026-05-27 (unit-test runner wired)
+
+Task 4 of the breakdown is now implemented, completing the testing gap noted
+above. No change to the decision — this hardens it.
+
+- Added `tsx@^4` as a devDependency and `test` / `test:watch` scripts to
+  `package.json` (`tsx --test "src/**/*.test.ts"`). Chose tsx over vitest to
+  stay on Node's built-in test runner (zero new test-framework surface; the
+  existing `amount.test.ts` already targets `node:test`).
+- `npm test` → 12/12 pass. Updated the stale runner comment in `amount.test.ts`.
+- No GitHub Actions workflow exists in the repo, so there is no CI pipeline to
+  attach a step to; `npm test` is the CI-ready entry point for when one is added.
+- Remaining open tasks (5 SMS/OCR adapter, 6 Plaid adapter) stay blocked on
+  adapters not yet present in the repo — unchanged.
+

